        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Bromley Kent</placeName>
                    <date>Ap. 11.</date>
                    <salute>My dear Hooker</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>In a note received this morning, Huxley mentions poor dear Henslow’s death.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> Thank God his sufferings are over.— I need not say how truly I sympathise with M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Hooker’s &amp; your own grief.— I think he was the best, the most noble character I ever knew. It will ever do one good to think of him.—</p>
<p>My dear friend | Yours affectionately | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The letter from <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2486.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Thomas Henry Huxley</ref> has not been found. CD had misunderstood Huxley’s note: <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2235.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">John Stevens Henslow</ref> was seriously ill but still alive. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-3119.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. D. Hooker, 14 [April 1861]</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
